values:
OOC: Started my new job recently, havent had time to really write, between the 10 hours day and then Casey it seems like i dont have time for Cam stuff any more. Work does give me time to think about cam stuff though which is good. I have decided to try a different style of writing, for some reason recounting game in story form doesnt seem to appeal as much to me. Hoping this idea will work a bit more and make it easier to account for what happened. Input is always appreciated. Please forgive the tags and html problem, its 4:30 in the morning and i suck at HTML in my prime let alone when my brain is fried from work.


IC: 

Demitri sits down at his desk pulling out a leather clad journal. Flipping through the old pages he couldn't help but chuckle remembering various events from the various days on the pages. Finally reaching a blank page, he reached for his quill pin, dipping it in the ink and slowly starting to scribe across the paper.

The Lamar nights find me well, so well I hardly have time to write like I used too. Sometimes I miss the days of old when all I had to do was rule over a bunch of peasants. Before my embrace when the days were spent running the fields on horseback, enjoying whatever women perked my interest. Now my time is politics, Invictus politics. At times I hate it; I hate the stupid people I have to deal with, and then I remember the power I have over them and I love it. I came across a spy in my ranks on Saturday. It saddened me to think that he believed in the Carthian ideals so much that he lied and risked his life to infilitrate the Invictus. I called him forward before my boardroom and gave him his options. Either renounce his Carthian ideals, or embrace the dark slumber. His refusal to answer spoke volumes. I had no choice but to order my thorned wreath to stake him. They presented his body to Prince Fetch who gave us premission to do with the spy as I pleased. He should be in a box on his way to the Davea Elders for  "proper education" on what to and not to do. Personally I thought walking blind into an Invictus gathering, alone and forgotten, should be top on the list. But what do I know?  Another public display of ignorance had to be addressed; a kindred decided to broadcast the prince's court over his cell phone to help a kindred who couldn't make it. Luckly the prince took it in stride and I didn't have to punish him openly.

The night was, to say the least, interesting. The sheriff put on a gathering which seemed to bring EVERYONE out of the woodworks. Who is there upon my arrival, none other then my first childe Mackenzie. The last time I saw her was during the Lamar Brood Seige. After the main conflict, I had lost my arm and she took care of my wounds...along with other things. Then I woke up one night and she had dissapeared into the night. Low and behold here she was back in town and on the arm of that pathetic excuse for a Nos, Michael also known as MIA. I had to have Mrs. Mattox slap me to help regain my composure or else the beast would have taken me and I would have ripped his arm off and beat him into torpor with it. But oh the night got even better. Yet ANOTHER child came out of nothwere. Jonas, a failed expirement of taking a nobody and refining them into a proper member of society. His spite for my failed attempts had not been transcended by time. The direction the night went from there, I cannot figure out, for everything bad that happened something good came out of it. The Crones all being locked in a room at the beckon of the prince and about to be firebombed brought nothing but joy to my face. That joy was crushed when I found out that Mack was trapped in the room as well. The feud betwen the Crones and the Invictus nearly cost me my child. Something I could not accept. So once lines of communications were opened and their Heirophant, myself, and the prince set down to discuss the past months, I did the only thing I could. I took the higher road and met him on neutral ground. Mattox's fight with Tillinghast had turned into a covenant war, due too Tillinghast insane .... I don't even know the word of how to describe it. Luckly a quick political took care of the problem completely. Putting myself between them and by the order of the prince, making sure that all interactions from Tillinghast came through me first completely eliviated the feud. Mattox will be free to pursue her Nos wishes without having to deal with his incessive dabbling and he cannot act against the Invictus without drawing the wrath of the prince. Sometimes I impress myself. 

So much happened and so little ink. As the dawn draws near I wonder what will happen. But not even I have the answers too that. Only time will tell.

Slowly closing the book Demitri leaned back in his chair, closing his eyes and crossing his fingers he couldn't help but chuckle. Lamar was becoming his, one night at a time. He had the backing of House Mattox, soon he would be named Seneshal, and the Invictus were quickly becoming  the most powerful covenant in the city. It was a good Requium.

The cold night air continued to beat onto Alex's face. It was a 15 hour drive back to Lamar and he had taken about 6 of it off in 4 hours time. He was pleased with his progress, he would beat the dawn, thats all that mattered to him. The ride gave him perfect time to think about what happened in Detroit, thinking over every event like an individual scene, replaying it in his head, watching the actors play our their parts over and over again. Acting, he had done a little bit of that himself in Detroit. He played his part in the play of life, and even now he couldnt figure out why. His mind drifted back to the old warehouse. The gangrel had regrouped after Bell Island, to help those who needed to feed, feed, and to figure out what exactly had happened. Well that idea went to complete shit real quick. Morality, thats what started it all. Not even an hour ago they had just massacred one their own kind, and yet they fretted over killing a mortal while feeding. It hurt his head to think about, where was the line drawn, and why did they get to pick who lived and who died. Everyone had that choice though, he knew that now, because he too had made the choice of life and death. He remebered the moment perfectly, their was gangrel everywhere, Aspasia's child held her as she fed, Tessa faught to get the mortal away from her, Dementia was coping with Dallas' frenzy leading to his claws into her back, Carmilla desperatly tried to get him off of her, several unnamed gangrel stood around the room confused and unable to decide on what to do. Then their was Alex, he stood their, admist all the chaos, the center of it all yet nobody was paying attention to him. He stood there, watching as carmilla held Dallas, begging for him to stop, the sound of Dementia's sobs, he swore he could hear her heart break, in that single moment he knew he had the power of life and death. He knew, in that moment he could have easly extended his claws and rammed them right through Dallas' chest. It would have been flawless, in one swipe killing one of the most powerful vampires in the States. He could have killed Dallas, and been gone with the wind before anyone even comprehended what he had done. As he stood their though, he knew what he had to do. And with one single motion he turned to stop the interference of another gangrel, another gangrel who would have done what he had thought about doing. In a single moment he had chosen for Dallas to live. Alex knew that Dallas was needed, their in Detroit, in Lamar, Dallas had pourpose, and it was not Alex's right to choose death and take away that pourpose, not yet anyway. He remebered the smell of the blood in the air, it reaked of death. In that room of death though he chose life. He felt good about himself for it though. He knew that one day it would probably come back to kill him. He was positive that Dallas would not give him the same courtesy, that given the same situation and same choice Dallas would have killed him in a heartbeat. Dallas would never know the decisions that were made, never realise what happened in the backstage of that play, and its probably for the best. All things aside it gave him a bit of hope, for better or for worse he had made a choice right that he doubted Dallas would or could have made. In Alex's eyes that was one thing he had over Dallas, even if it was something nobody would ever know, HE knew, and thats what mattered to him. Because if their was one thing, their could be more, and that was a sign of hope, and hope what was mattered most of all to him.

It had been a long trip home for Alex, the cold Detroit air blew against him as his bike roared down the highway. He hoped to make Lamar by dawn, he yearned too see Meredith. He didn't know how much was the blood and how much was his own personal feelings, but he knew it was their. He weaved in and out of traffic, racing the post dusk traffic. He had set out as soon as possible, dodging every vehicle as he sped past, his leather jacket gripping his body tightly. The air rushed past his head, blowing his hair backwards, it reminded him of something... Bell Island, he remembered the wind blowing after the Star Maker fell, it howled in pain and anger, blowing like a sick gale. He remembered the spirits as they started to tear into kindred around him. He pitied some of them, those that were being torn at by the spirits, screaming in pain as they fled the island. He himself was granted with the gift of mist, and left effortlessly, others were not so fortunate. As he left though he remembered the sight of Dallas and Aspasia, enduring the event, like mortals who refused to leave there homes knowing a tornado was coming. He respected Aspasia, when she spoke she made him feel like there WAS hope for the kindred society, that they were not as damned as he had always thought. Then he remembered Dallas, he hated Dallas, it was a hate that nobody would ever understand, because it was a hate underlined by respect. As Alex floated off the island in his mist form he looked back, watching the spirits tear into Dallas, and he stood their, enduring, unshaken by the events around him. Alex hated Dallas for being so strong, he hated the both strength and integrity that he displayed. He hated how he felt like a god anywhere else he went, but when he was around Dallas, he was nothing. He went to Detroit too get away from Lamar and the damn pack, and low and behold their was Dallas. Everyone he met, the question always arose "Did you come with Dallas?" The sudden honking of horns snapped Alex back to reality as he realized he had drifted into the other lane, a car swerved bye barely missing him as he jerked the handle bars getting the back on the right side of the road. He took a deep breath, regaining his composure, running his hand through his hair. Most of all though, he hated Dallas because he couldn't hate him, no more then petty jealousy. After Aspasia's speech he knew what Dallas did in Lamar was needed, and he hated him for it.

Time passed and Alex reflected his time in Detroit, the star's filled the sky as he exited the outskirts of the city, greeting the open road and answering its call. Hours passed and he pulled into a rest stop, his bike rolled too a stop and he couldn't help but sit their, staring up into the sky. He wondered if Meredith was staring up at the same sky, the same sky they stared up at together before he left. He remembered how he had promised her how he would come back, and coming back he was, safe and sound.

"I'm coming back for ya baby, just wait for me a little bit longer."

Alex stared up for a moment more before restarting his bike and aiming it south, prepared to race the coming sun.
